SIMPLE: pall-mall
RECORDS: 1

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Pall-mall
<hw>Pall`-mall"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OF.
<ets>palemail</ets>, It. <ets>pallamagio</ets>; <ets>palla</ets> a ball
(of German origin, akin to E. <ets>ball</ets>) + <ets>magio</ets>
hammer, fr. L. <ets>malleus</ets>. See 1st <er>Ball</er>, and
<er>Mall</er> a beetle.]</ety> <def>A game formerly common in England,
in which a wooden ball was driven with a mallet through an elevated hoop
or ring of iron. The name was also given to the mallet used, to the
place where the game was played, and to the street, in London, still
called <etsep>Pall Mall</etsep>.</def> <altsp>[Written also
<asp>pail-mail</asp> and <asp>pell-mell</asp>.]</altsp> <rj><au>Sir K.
Digby.</au> <au>Evelyn.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Pallone</ent>⟦br⟧
